content.description: The crux is leaving the block pinch and going for gold.
content.location: Face the boulder from trailside view. Follow the obvious lip downward and right to the end. Standing here, you'll find a thin, shallow pinch for your left hand and a big honkin' right hand slopey block pinch up and right of it. Find a foot hold, and match on the slopey block pinch. Throw your left heel on the left hand start, pump, and bump up high and right to a tiny nugget. Lock off and hand-foot match to gain the block pinch. Once you've gained it, bump up and right to the obvious sidepull. Then just step on home plate, and look for high fives.

content.description: The foot holds are fleeting until after the 7th inning stretch.
content.location: From the trailside view, walk around the right side. You'll see a left-ascending ledge. Look below it to a sharp left hand crimp and right hand edge at crouch level. Establish yourself, and flex up into the ledge above. Find high foot holds, then move up the ledge. Match on the highest (leftmost) part of ledge, then make a big move out right, and watch the barn door. Get your balance, and enjoy a trouble free topout.

From the trailside view, walk around the right side. You'll see a leftward-ascending ledge. Stand start with your hands high on a ledge. Find high foot holds, then move up and left to a no gimme topout.

content.description: Burbank Boulder is a proud-looking 10-footer perched atop NE finest bedrock. Much of the block is unclimbable, but there's at least three viable routes, likely more. A downclimb is best on backside to the right.
